<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,384,1638,1664]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Ampittia kilombero</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Larsen" box="[392,705,1638,1664]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" refString="Larsen, T. C. E. &amp; Congdon, T. C. E. (2012) The genus Ampittia in Africa with the description of a new species (Hesperiinae; Aeromachini) and three new species in the genera Andronymus and Chondrolepis (Hesperiinae, incertae sedis) (Lepidoptera; Hesperiidae). Zootaxa, 3322, 49 - 62." type="journal article" year="2012">
Larsen &amp; Congdon, 
<number box="[647,705,1638,1664]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="2012.0">2012</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[721,869,1638,1664]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 4" captionStart-1="FIGURE 5" captionStartId-0="4.[151,250,779,802]" captionStartId-1="4.[151,250,1700,1723]" captionTargetBox-0="[151,1435,151,767]" captionTargetBox-1="[151,1435,869,1686]" captionTargetId-0="figure@4.[151,1436,135,768]" captionTargetId-1="figure@4.[151,1436,869,1687]" captionTargetPageId-0="4" captionTargetPageId-1="4" captionText-0="FIGURE 4. Final instar caterpillar of Ampittia kilombero on unidentified grass, Mngeta, Kilombero Valley, S Tanzania, 450 m, 23 – 27 May 2010, TCEC. 1, dorsolateral view; 2, lateral view; 3, head anterior view; 4, posterior segments, dorsal view." captionText-1="FIGURE 5. Pupa of Ampittia kilombero collected on unidentified grass, Mngeta, Kilombero Valley, S Tanzania, 450 m, 20 May 2010, 12 mm, TCEC. 1, dorsal view; 2, lateral view." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/246335/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/246336/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Figures 
<number box="[824,869,1638,1664]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="4.5" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="4.0">4–5</number>
</figureCitation>
)
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1638,2021]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
This newly described species is only known from two colonies in the 
<taxonomicName box="[933,1054,1673,1697]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Ampittia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kilombero">Kilombero</taxonomicName>
Valley at the south-eastern end of the Udzungwa Mountains, 
<collectingCountry box="[458,558,1709,1733]" name="Tanzania" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Tanzania</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Larsen" box="[575,864,1709,1733]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" refString="Larsen, T. C. E. &amp; Congdon, T. C. E. (2012) The genus Ampittia in Africa with the description of a new species (Hesperiinae; Aeromachini) and three new species in the genera Andronymus and Chondrolepis (Hesperiinae, incertae sedis) (Lepidoptera; Hesperiidae). Zootaxa, 3322, 49 - 62." type="journal article" year="2012">
Larsen &amp; Congdon 
<number box="[803,864,1709,1733]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="2012.0">2012</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). It seems to be a species of open wetland, where the food plant is an unidentified fine-leaved grass. The caterpillar (
<figureCitation box="[911,1009,1745,1769]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="4.[151,250,779,802]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,151,767]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,135,768]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 4. Final instar caterpillar of Ampittia kilombero on unidentified grass, Mngeta, Kilombero Valley, S Tanzania, 450 m, 23 – 27 May 2010, TCEC. 1, dorsolateral view; 2, lateral view; 3, head anterior view; 4, posterior segments, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/246335/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Figure 
<number box="[994,1009,1745,1769]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
) is green with a pale lateral line, dark speckles T 
<number box="[271,312,1781,1805]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="2.5" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.0">2–3</number>
and anal plate; a narrow black dorsal plate T 
<number box="[825,836,1781,1805]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="1.0">1</number>
; a pale brown head with dark brown markings—very different from that of 
<taxonomicName box="[392,514,1817,1841]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Ampittia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capenas">
<emphasis box="[392,514,1817,1841]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">A. capenas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[528,625,1817,1841]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,520,543]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,153,498]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,153,498]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Final instar caterpillar of Ampittia capenas on unidentified grass, Rondo Plateau, SE Tanzania, 850 m, 0 9 Feb 2005, TCEC. 1, dorsal view; 2, head anterior view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/246333/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Figure 
<number box="[609,625,1817,1841]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
); pale brown spiracles. The spiracles visible on A 
<number box="[1185,1198,1817,1841]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="7.0">7</number>
–A 
<quantity box="[1235,1275,1817,1841]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.032" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" unit="in" value="8.0">8 in</quantity>
Figure 
<number box="[1360,1395,1817,1841]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="4.4">4.4</number>
are distinctly projecting; we have not noticed spiracles of this form in any other 
<taxonomicName box="[1014,1152,1853,1877]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Hesperiidae</taxonomicName>
. The pupa is cylindrical, white, with pale brown spiracles (
<figureCitation box="[539,639,1889,1913]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1700,1723]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,869,1686]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,869,1687]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 5. Pupa of Ampittia kilombero collected on unidentified grass, Mngeta, Kilombero Valley, S Tanzania, 450 m, 20 May 2010, 12 mm, TCEC. 1, dorsal view; 2, lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/246336/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Figure 
<number box="[623,639,1889,1913]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
). Like that of 
<taxonomicName box="[814,939,1889,1913]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Ampittia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capenas">
<emphasis box="[814,939,1889,1913]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">A. capenas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, it has two frontal projections, but directed anterolaterally, not laterally. As for 
<taxonomicName box="[555,678,1926,1950]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Ampittia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capenas">
<emphasis box="[555,678,1926,1950]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">A. capenas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the pupa was formed in a closed grass leaf tube and attached at the cremaster. It was most inconspicuous, the blade having been partially severed so that the portion containing the pupa was hanging down.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
